A function is invertible if and only if it is one-to-one.  This means that no two different inputs produce the same output.  We can check this visually by looking for any horizontal lines that intersect the graph more than once.

Consider the function $g(x) = f(x) + ax$.  Adding a constant to the output of $f(x)$ shifts the graph vertically.  Adding a multiple of $x$ to the output of $f(x)$ stretches or compresses the graph horizontally.  Thus, we can adjust the values of $a$ and $b$ to make the graph of $g(x)$ or $h(x)$ one-to-one.

To make the graph of $g(x)$ one-to-one, we need to shift the graph of $f(x)$ so that it passes the horizontal line test.  We can do this by choosing a value of $a$ that is large enough to make the graph of $g(x)$ strictly increasing or strictly decreasing.

To make the graph of $h(x)$ one-to-one, we need to choose a value of $b$ that is large enough to make the graph of $h(x)$ strictly increasing or strictly decreasing.

